      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-6">The Algebra of Grade Planning: Solving for Final Exam Targets</h2>
      <div class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>
          As semesters draw to a close, students often ask: **"What do I need on my final exam to pass or get an A?"** Running these calculations manually requires algebraic equations, but our tool handles the variables instantly.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">The Grade Requirement Equation</h3>
        <p>
          A class grade is calculated as a weighted average combining your current class grade and your final exam score. By rearranging this equation to isolate the required final exam score, we get:
          <br />
          <strong class="block my-2 text-center text-ink font-mono text-xs">Required Final Score = [Target Grade - Current Grade &times; (1 - Final Weight)] / Final Weight</strong>
          Where:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 font-sans text-sm">
          <li><strong>Target Grade:</strong> The final percentage you want to achieve in the class (e.g. 90% for an A).</li>
          <li><strong>Current Grade:</strong> Your class average leading up to the final exam (e.g. 85%).</li>
          <li><strong>Final Exam Weight:</strong> The percentage weight your final exam holds in the syllabus (e.g. 20%).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Interpreting Your Required Score</h3>
        <p>
          Depending on your coursework average and the final exam's weight:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 font-sans text-sm">
          <li><strong>Under 70%:</strong> Highly achievable. Your steady homework and midterm performance has built a comfortable buffer.</li>
          <li><strong>90% to 100%:</strong> Challenging. Requires focused studying, as minor mistakes on the final can prevent you from hitting your target grade.</li>
          <li><strong>Over 100%:</strong> Extra credit needed. It is mathematically impossible to reach your target grade with standard scores, meaning that a curved grading scale is required.</li>
        </ul>
      
<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Understanding Syllabus Weight Distributions</h3>
        <p>
          Course syllabi vary in how grades are calculated. Some instructors use a straight points system, where your final grade is simply total points earned divided by total points possible. However, many college and high school courses use a weighted categories system, where different types of assignments contribute a set percentage to your final grade. A standard syllabus weight distribution might look like this: Homework 20%, Quizzes 20%, Midterms 30%, and the Final Exam 30%. Under this system, a single low homework grade has a minor impact, while a poor grade on a heavily weighted final exam can significantly change your overall grade.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Scenario: Calculating Your Final Exam Target</h3>
        <p>
          Let's walk through a practical scenario to find out what grade you need on a final exam. Suppose you have an 84% average in your chemistry class heading into the final exam, and you want to earn a B+ (87%) overall. The final exam is weighted at 25% of your course grade, meaning your current coursework accounts for the remaining 75%.
        </p>
        <p>
          To calculate your target grade, first multiply your current average by its weight: <code>84 &times; 0.75 = 63</code> points. This means you have secured 63 points toward your final grade.
        </p>
        <p>
          To reach 87 points overall, you need to earn 24 more points from the final exam: <code>87 - 63 = 24</code>. Divide these required points by the exam's weight: <code>24 / 0.25 = 96%</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The math indicates you must score a 96% on the final exam to achieve an 87% overall in the course. Our calculator handles this math instantly, helping you set study goals and prepare for finals.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Strategies for Borderline Grades</h3>
        <p>
          If you are on the borderline between two letter grades (e.g., an 89.4% average and you need a 90% for an A-), calculating your required exam score can help reduce test anxiety. Knowing the exact percentage target allows you to budget your study time across different classes. Sometimes, a high score on the final can pull your grade up, while a lower score can drop it down. Use our calculator to identify which classes require the most focus.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Point-Based Grading Systems vs. Weight-Based Systems</h3>
        <p>
          In a point-based grading system, every point is worth the same amount. For example, if a homework assignment is worth 10 points and a midterm is worth 100 points, the midterm has ten times the impact. In a weight-based system, category weights determine the final grade, regardless of how many points are in each category. If homework is weighted at 30% and tests at 70%, the total points in each category are scaled to match those percentages, which is a common point of confusion for students.
        </p>
